  "The appendicular skeleton consists of approximately 126 bones, including those of the upper limbs, lower limbs, pectoral girdle, and pelvic girdle.": "",
  "The pectoral (shoulder) girdle consists of the:": "",
  "Vertebrae": "",
  "Sternum and ribs": "",
  "Clavicle and scapula": "",
  "Hip bones": "",
  "The pectoral girdle on each side is composed of the clavicle (collarbone) anteriorly and the scapula (shoulder blade) posteriorly, which together attach the upper limb to the axial skeleton.": "",
  "The single bone of the upper arm is the:": "",
  "Radius": "",
  "Ulna": "",
  "Humerus": "",
  "Femur": "",
  "The humerus is the single bone of the upper arm (brachium), extending from the shoulder to the elbow, where it articulates with both the radius and ulna of the forearm.": "",
  "The forearm contains how many bones?": "",
  "Four: two proximal and two distal segments": "",
  "Two: the radius and ulna": "",
  "Three: radius, ulna, and an interosseous bone": "",
  "One: a single fused forearm bone": "",
  "The forearm (antebrachium) contains two bones: the radius on the lateral (thumb) side and the ulna on the medial (pinky) side, which work together to allow pronation and supination.": "",
  "The longest bone in the body is the:": "",
  "Fibula": "",
  "Tibia": "",
  "The femur (thighbone) is the longest, heaviest, and strongest bone in the human body, extending from the hip joint to the knee joint.": "",
  "How many carpal bones are in each wrist?": "",
  "8": "",
  "5": "",
  "10": "",
  "6": "",
  "Each wrist contains 8 carpal bones arranged in two rows of four, which together form a flexible and stable wrist joint.": "",
  "The tibia is the:": "",
  "Larger, weight-bearing bone of the lower leg (shinbone)": "",
  "Smaller, lateral bone of the lower leg": "",
  "Forearm bone": "",
  "Thighbone": "",
  "The tibia (shinbone) is the larger, medial bone of the lower leg that bears the majority of the body's weight and articulates with the femur at the knee joint.": "",
  "Each hip bone is formed by the fusion of how many bones?": "",
  "4 bones: ilium, ischium, pubis, and acetabular ring": "",
  "3 bones: ilium, ischium, and pubis": "",
  "1 bone: a single unified coxal plate": "",
  "2 bones: the ilium and a fused ischiopubic ramus": "",
  "Each hip bone (os coxae) is formed by the fusion of three bones: the ilium (superior), ischium (posteroinferior), and pubis (anteroinferior). These three bones fuse at the acetabulum during adolescence.": "",
  "How many phalanges are in each hand?": "",
  "15": "",
  "14": "",
  "20": "",
  "Each hand contains 14 phalanges: 2 in the thumb (proximal and distal) and 3 in each of the other four fingers (proximal, middle, and distal), for a total of 14.": "",
  "The radius is located on which side of the forearm?": "",
  "Superior": "",
  "Inferior": "",
  "Lateral (thumb side)": "",
  "Medial (pinky side)": "",
  "In the anatomical position, the radius is the lateral forearm bone located on the thumb side. It is the primary forearm bone that articulates with the carpal bones at the wrist.": "",
  "What is the pectoral girdle?": "",
  "The bones that form the hip and pelvic region": "",
  "The clavicle and scapula on each side that attach the upper limb to the axial skeleton": "",
  "The cervical vertebrae that support the shoulder": "",
  "The rib cage and sternum": "",
  "The pectoral (shoulder) girdle consists of the clavicle and scapula on each side of the body. It connects the bones of the upper limb to the axial skeleton and is designed for maximum mobility rather than stability.": "",
  "What is the acetabulum?": "",
  "The shallow socket of the shoulder joint on the scapula": "",
  "The deep, cup-shaped socket on the hip bone where the femoral head articulates": "",
  "The point where the three hip bones meet during development": "",
  "The opening in the hip bone for blood vessels": "",
  "The acetabulum is the deep, cup-shaped socket on the lateral surface of the hip bone where the head of the femur articulates to form the hip joint. It is formed at the junction of the ilium, ischium, and pubis.": "",
  "What is the fibula?": "",
  "The kneecap": "",
  "The medial bone of the forearm": "",
  "The larger, weight-bearing bone of the lower leg": "",
  "The thin, lateral bone of the lower leg that primarily serves for muscle attachment": "",
  "The fibula is the slender, lateral bone of the lower leg that does not bear significant body weight. Its primary functions are providing attachment sites for muscles and forming the lateral wall of the ankle joint.": "",
  "What is the olecranon?": "",
  "A projection on the femur near the hip joint": "",
  "The bony prominence at the proximal end of the ulna that forms the point of the elbow": "",
  "A process on the radius that forms part of the wrist joint": "",
  "The bump on the scapula at the top of the shoulder": "",
  "The olecranon is the large bony process at the proximal end of the ulna that forms the point of the elbow. It fits into the olecranon fossa of the humerus during elbow extension and serves as an attachment for the triceps muscle.": "",
  "What is the calcaneus?": "",
  "The ankle bone that sits on top of the foot": "",
  "A bone in the arch of the foot": "",
  "The largest tarsal bone, forming the heel of the foot": "",
  "The calcaneus is the largest of the 7 tarsal bones and forms the prominence of the heel. It supports body weight when standing and serves as the attachment point for the Achilles tendon.": "",
  "What is the ilium?": "",
  "The socket of the hip joint": "",
  "The large, fan-shaped superior portion of the hip bone whose crest you can feel at your waist": "",
  "The posteroinferior portion of the hip bone you sit on": "",
  "The anteroinferior portion of the hip bone that forms the pubic symphysis": "",
  "The ilium is the largest of the three hip bones, forming the broad, fan-shaped superior portion. Its superior border, the iliac crest, is the bony ridge you can palpate at your waist and is a common site for bone marrow biopsies.": "",
  "What does the term pelvic girdle mean?": "",
  "The two hip bones (os coxae) that connect the lower limbs to the axial skeleton": "",
  "The femurs and their surrounding muscles": "",
  "Only the sacrum and coccyx at the base of the spine": "",
  "The clavicle and scapula on each side of the body": "",
  "The pelvic girdle consists of the two hip bones (os coxae) that connect the lower limbs to the axial skeleton. Together with the sacrum, they form the bony pelvis, which supports body weight and protects pelvic organs.": "",
  "What are metacarpals?": "",
  "The eight small bones of the wrist": "",
  "The bones of the sole of the foot": "",
  "The five bones of the palm that connect the carpals to the phalanges": "",
  "The bones of the fingers and thumb": "",
  "The metacarpals are the five miniature long bones of the palm of the hand, numbered I through V from thumb to pinky. They articulate with the carpals proximally and with the phalanges distally.": "",
  "What is the patella?": "",
  "The bump on the lateral side of the ankle": "",
  "A carpal bone in the wrist": "",
  "The sesamoid bone embedded in the quadriceps tendon at the front of the knee": "",
  "A tarsal bone in the ankle": "",
  "The patella (kneecap) is the largest sesamoid bone in the body, embedded within the tendon of the quadriceps femoris muscle. It protects the anterior knee joint and increases the mechanical leverage of the quadriceps.": "",
  "What does it mean that the female pelvis is wider and shallower than the male pelvis?": "",
  "The female pelvis is weaker and more prone to fracture": "",
  "The female pelvis has fewer bones than the male pelvis": "",
  "The female pelvis is adapted for childbirth, with a broader inlet and wider subpubic angle to allow passage of the fetal head": "",
  "The female pelvis cannot support as much body weight as the male pelvis": "",
  "The female pelvis has a wider, more circular pelvic inlet and a wider subpubic angle compared to the male pelvis. These adaptations create a larger birth canal to facilitate the passage of the fetal head during childbirth.": "",
  "A patient falls on an outstretched hand and reports wrist pain in the anatomical snuffbox area. X-rays initially appear normal, but the physician suspects a fracture of a specific carpal bone that is notorious for poor blood supply. Which bone is most likely fractured?": "",
  "Lunate": "",
  "Capitate": "",
  "Scaphoid": "",
  "Trapezium": "",
  "The scaphoid is the most commonly fractured carpal bone, typically from a fall on an outstretched hand. It is notorious for poor blood supply to its proximal pole, which can lead to avascular necrosis if the fracture is not properly treated.": "",
  "An elderly patient trips and falls on the sidewalk. She presents to the emergency department with severe hip pain and an externally rotated, shortened leg. The orthopedic surgeon suspects a fracture of the femoral neck. Why is this injury so common and dangerous in elderly patients?": "",
  "The femoral neck has no periosteum to aid in healing": "",
  "Osteoporosis weakens the femoral neck, and fracture here can disrupt the blood supply to the femoral head, risking avascular necrosis": "",
  "The femoral neck is not part of the appendicular skeleton": "",
  "The femoral neck is made entirely of cartilage in elderly patients": "",
  "The femoral neck is a common fracture site in elderly osteoporotic patients because the weakened bone cannot withstand the force of a fall. This fracture is particularly dangerous because it can disrupt the blood supply to the femoral head, leading to avascular necrosis.": "",
  "A physical therapist is working with a patient who dislocated her shoulder. She explains that shoulder dislocations are far more common than hip dislocations. Why is the shoulder more prone to dislocation?": "",
  "The shoulder has more bones that can be displaced": "",
  "The humerus is heavier than the femur and pulls the joint apart": "",
  "The glenoid cavity of the scapula is shallow, sacrificing stability for greater range of motion compared to the deep acetabulum of the hip": "",
  "The shoulder has no ligaments to stabilize it": "",
  "The shoulder joint has a shallow glenoid cavity on the scapula, which allows the greatest range of motion of any joint but provides less bony stability. The hip joint, in contrast, has the deep acetabulum that tightly encloses the femoral head, making dislocation rare.": "",
  "A runner develops pain along the front of the lower leg (shin splints). Her sports medicine physician explains that the larger, medial bone of the lower leg bears most of the body weight during running. Which bone is the physician referring to?": "",
  "The talus": "",
  "The tibia": "",
  "The fibula": "",
  "The femur": "",
  "The tibia (shinbone) is the larger, medial bone of the lower leg that bears the majority of the body's weight. Repetitive stress from running can cause inflammation along the tibial periosteum, producing the condition commonly known as shin splints.": "",
  "A forensic anthropologist is asked to determine the sex of a skeleton found at an excavation site. She focuses on the pelvis for the most reliable determination. What key feature would indicate the skeleton is female?": "",
  "A wide, circular pelvic inlet with a wide subpubic angle (greater than 90 degrees)": "",
  "Thicker, heavier hip bones with prominent muscle attachment sites": "",
  "An acetabulum that faces more laterally": "",
  "A narrow, heart-shaped pelvic inlet with a narrow subpubic angle": "",
  "The female pelvis is characterized by a wide, circular pelvic inlet and a wide subpubic angle (typically greater than 90 degrees), both of which are adaptations for childbirth. The male pelvis is narrower with a heart-shaped inlet and a more acute subpubic angle.": "",
  "A college student falls off a skateboard and lands on an outstretched arm. He presents with pain at the middle of the collarbone and a visible bump. The X-ray confirms a midshaft clavicle fracture. Why is this the most commonly fractured bone?": "",
  "The clavicle has no blood supply and is therefore weak": "",
  "The clavicle is exposed because it is not covered by any muscles": "",
  "The clavicle is a sesamoid bone with a thin cortex": "",
  "The clavicle is the only bony strut connecting the upper limb to the axial skeleton and transmits forces from the arm to the trunk, making it vulnerable during falls": "",
  "The clavicle is the most commonly fractured bone because it acts as the sole bony strut connecting the upper limb to the trunk. When a person falls on an outstretched hand, the force is transmitted through the arm to the clavicle, which can fracture at its thinnest midshaft region.": "",
  "A basketball player lands awkwardly and reports severe ankle pain. The athletic trainer palpates a bony bump on the inner side of the ankle that is very tender. Which bone structure is likely injured?": "",
  "The lateral malleolus of the fibula": "",
  "The calcaneus (heel bone)": "",
  "The medial malleolus of the tibia": "",
  "The medial malleolus is the bony prominence on the inner (medial) side of the ankle, formed by the distal end of the tibia. Ankle fractures commonly involve the medial malleolus, especially during inversion or eversion injuries.": "",
  "A patient presents with Achilles tendon pain at the back of the heel. The physician explains that the tendon attaches to the largest bone of the foot. Which bone is the physician describing?": "",
  "The navicular": "",
  "The first metatarsal": "",
  "The calcaneus": "",
  "The calcaneus (heel bone) is the largest tarsal bone and serves as the attachment point for the Achilles (calcaneal) tendon. The powerful pull of the calf muscles is transmitted through this tendon to the calcaneus to enable plantarflexion during walking and running.": "",
